Prerequisites

library(sf)
library(raster)
library(dplyr)
library(spData)
library(spDataLarge)
library(tmap)

tmap basics

Add fill layer to New Zealand shape

tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_fill()

Add just borders

tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_borders()

Add fill and border layers

tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_fill() +
  tm_borders()

map objects

  • tmap can store maps as objects
  • this means that we store a base map and add additional layers later
map_nz <- tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_polygons()
class(map_nz)
## [1] "tmap"
  • we can add new shapes on top of the base map
  • when we add a new shape, all subsequent aesthetic functions refer to it, until we add a new shape
  • in this case, we’re adding a layer with information on elevation
  • we modify this layer to have 70% transparency
map_nz1 <- map_nz +
  tm_shape(nz_elev) +
  tm_raster(alpha = 0.7)

map_nz1 
## stars object downsampled to 877 by 1140 cells. See tm_shape manual (argument raster.downsample)

map_nz2 <- map_nz1 +
  tm_shape(nz_height) +
  tm_dots()

map_nz2
## stars object downsampled to 877 by 1140 cells. See tm_shape manual (argument raster.downsample)
